@<!DOCTYPE doctype PUBLIC "-//w3c//dtd html 4.0 transitional//en">
<html>
  <head>
    <meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html;
      charset=windows-1252">
    <meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/4.73 [en] (X11; I; Linux
      2.2.17 i686) [Netscape]">
    <meta name="author" content="Marc Gloor">
    <title>xmon for Linux</title>
  </head>
  <body link="#0000ef" vlink="#55188a" text="#000000" alink="#ff0000"
    bgcolor="#ffffff">
    <b><font size="+1">xmon - minimalistic lightweight system
        performance monitor</font></b> <br>
    by Marc O. Gloor <br>
    <hr width="100%">
    <p><b>Abstract</b> </p>
    <p data-path-to-node="4">Xmon is a minimalistic lightweight system
      performance monitor for Linux. It visualizes real-time system
      load, memory usage, and CPU activity. The tool operates by reading
      data directly from the Linux process filesystem (/proc), which
      must be mounted for the application to function.<br>
      <br>
      &nbsp; * CPU Usage <b>[</b><font color="#ffcc00"><b>CPU</b></font><b>]</b>:
      Total processor utilization (central parallel unit usage)<br>
      &nbsp; * Memory <b>[</b><b><font color="#ff0000">MEM</font></b><b>]</b>:
      Current RAM consumption (used memory)<br>
      &nbsp; * System Load <b>[</b><b><font color="#00cccc">LOAD</font></b><b>]</b>:
      Standard Linux load average (load average)<br>
      <br>
      As of Feb 2026 with release 0.0.4b, a minor vibe code
      modernization has been applied in order to brush-up the code and
      make it work with any modern Linux kernels and X11 environments,
      tested using most recent Debian SID (Feb 26). All features were
      hardcoded, command-line options are not supported. While the
      interface is designed to be self-explanatory, obviating the need
      for a manpage, please note that active development has concluded.
      Xmon was the result of a single-day Xlib API deep dive in 1998
      when I was a student, consequently, the codebase is in a beta
      state, largely unoptimized, and may contain bugs. A workaround for
      memory overflows has been included.</p>
    <p data-path-to-node="5">While not portable to other Unix
      derivatives like Solaris or AIX, it is compatible with any
      hardware (such as Sun or RS/6000) running a Linux environment. I
      am releasing the source code under the GNU GPL in the hope that
      it's useful for your daily use.<br>
      <br>
    </p>
    <p>
      <meta http-equiv="content-type" content="text/html;
        charset=windows-1252">
    </p>
    <b>Installation<br>
    </b><br>
    Source package: <a href="data/xmon-0.0.4b.tar.gz">xmon-0.0.4b.tar.gz</a>
    <br>
    Download, extract and follow the README instructions to compile and
    install xmon.<br>
    <br>
    Precompiled binary package: <a
href="file:///home/gloor/data/www/a_eigene/a_Website-current/data/xmon-0.0.4b-x86-statbin.tar.gz">xmon-0.0.4b-x86-statbin.tar.gz</a><br>
    Download Linux x86-64 ELF (amd64) binary distribution that runs out
    of the box.<br>
    <br>
    Debian binary package for amd64 architecture: <a
      href="data/xmon_0.0.4-1_amd64.deb">xmon_0.0.4-1_amd64.deb</a><br>
    Download and install using your package manager e.g. dpkg or apt. <br>
    <br>
    <br>
